    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I've been doing a lot of HIIT lately and I keep hearing people talk about \"lactic acid buildup\" and that burning sensation in the muscles. Can you explain the actual biochemistry of how lactic acid is produced during high intensity work and how the body clears it out afterwards?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "During HIIT, your body uses a high-intensity effort, leading to an overload of anaerobic energy production, which relies on stored energy sources like ATP and glycogen. As these stores are depleted, your body breaks down glucose into lactate through anaerobic glycolysis, producing lactic acid. This occurs in the muscle cells, primarily in your legs and core. As the lactic acid builds up, it causes the burning sensation and fatigue you mentioned. The body clears out lactic acid through several mechanisms, including increased blood flow to the affected muscles, fatigue compensation, and cellular uptake of lactate from the bloodstream.",
